We developed another approach for a scaffold-free MCS assembling system called a “needle-array” system (Figure 1.2
) that is slightly different from bio-printing systems. Instead of using hydrogel as the “bio-paper,” we used medical-grade stainless needles as temporal fixators to skewer MCSs until they fused with one another. This concept was inspired from surgical treatments for bone fracture in orthopedic surgery, called “external fixation” (Figure 1.3
). For treatment of bone fracture, orthopedic surgeons reposition fractured bone pieces to their original positions with or without surgery. After repositioning, surgeons immobilize bone pieces by using casts or splints without surgery or by using metal plates, screws, or pins under surgical procedure. Inspired from fracture treatment, especially by the external fixation technique, we developed the needle-array system. We also developed a robotic system that skewers MCSs into needle-array according to a three-dimensional design template (Figure 1.4
).
